result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred judgment agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed. The defendant has not been convicted of the dismissed charges.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Follow all conditions as set forth in signed Deferred Entry of Judgment Agreement.

judgments.action: Guilty Due to No Contest Plea

records.addlTxt: Defendant Alex L McGeshick in court with attorney Timothy B Melms.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 2:15 PM. State - here for FPT on 15CM141 - offer had a contingency that if accepted, State would not seek revocation on 15CM42 so no hearing on that matter is needed and State moves to dismiss that case at this time upon acceptance of plea offer, plead to #2 and #3 as allged, #2 - fine of $300.00 plus costs and surcharges totalling $1114.50, #3 - court costs only ($243.00) and dismiss count #1. Melms and McGeshick agree. Court dismisses count #1. McGeshick plead NC to counts #2 and #3 as alleged. Court dismisses DEJ on 15CM42. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - believes this case is eligible for expungement and comments positively on the appearance of the defendand in Court today. Melms makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. McGeshick withholds comment. Clerk informs Court that there is currently $1000.00 posted on 15CM42 and has $300.00 posted on 15CM141.  McGeshick makes statement, remorseful. Court sentences the defendant to the following: count #1 - $300 fine plus costs and surcharges totalling $1114.50 - take bond posted from 15CM42, count #3 - court costs only of $443.00 - take bond posted - remainder of $257.50 due today, authorizes expungement under 973.015 and upon payment of fine today, the record can be expunged, right to appeal, submit DNA sample and apply for the expungement of that, adjourned.

Defendant Alex L McGeshick in court with attorney Timothy B Melms.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 10:11 AM. Attorney Melms is taking over as counsel on both matters and has filed a Motion and Order for Substitution on Counsel. State - here for return on warrant on both cases. Melms has not gone over the complaint for 15CM141 with the defendant. Melms and McGeshick handed complaint in Court. Court reads charges and penalties on 15CM141. Melms and McGeshick understand charges and penalties, waives further reading, enters NG pleas to all counts on that matter. State - need to schedule 15CM42 for hearing to see if they are objecting to the revocation of the deferred entry of judgement. Melms requests a hearing on 15CM42 and to hear the matters together. State has no objections to that. Court sets both matters for hearings.  Court - bond - 15CM141 - $300 cash with no consumption of alcohol. 15CM42 - $1000 cash with no consumption of alcohol.  Hearing scheduled for April 20, 2016 at 01:45 pm.

Defendant Alex L McGeshick in court with attorney Mary L.R. Burns.  Charles Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 8:49 AM. State - resolved - defendant would plead to count #1 as alleged, dismiss and read in remaining counts, DEJ on count #1. Burns and McGeshick agree. McGeshick pleads NC to count #1 as alleged. Court dismisses and reads in counts #2 and #3. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, witholds finding of guilt and defers entry of the judgment. State has complied with victim notification. Court puts on the record the off the record telephone call yesterday in regards to this matter being settled and not going to JT, will be assessing jury fees to one party or both per statute. Court accepts DEJ and allows parties to make a statement/argument in regards to costs being assessed. State responds - reiterates the issues that were stated yesterday with the victim(s). Burns responds - if costs are going to be imposed on any party - suggests that costs be assessed to her and not the defendant for stated reasons. Court - imposes jury fees of $1000.00 against the State. State asks for guidance from the Court for a measure to accomodate such events happening in the future. Court responds - understands DA's office is under alot of pressure preparing for multiple trials at once. Adjourned at 9:12 AM.

Attorney Mary L.R. Burns in court - via telephone.   Charles Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Not on the record. Discussion between Chuck and Mary informing Court the status of the case (proceed to JT or accept DEJ). State - met with witnesses and victims this AM - offer is slightly different than original offer that was rejected. Burns responds - confirms what State has advised Court. Court responds regarding Court policy on pleading out prior to JT. Court responds with assessing jury fees to one party if jurors are called off. Court calls off the juror, will take the plea at 8:30 AM and will decide who to assees jury fees.
